Three students, with different names, line up single file. What is the probability that they are in alphabetical order from front-to-back?  Express your answer as a common fraction.
inference:
There are 3! = 6 possible orderings of the three students.  These are ABC, ACB, BAC, BCA, CAB, CBA.  Only one of these orderings (ABC) is in alphabetical order.  The probability is 1/6.
Final Answer: $\boxed{\frac{1}{6}}$. I hope it is correct.
ground_truth: There are six ways to line up: $ABC$, $ACB$, $BAC$, $BCA$, $CAB$, $CBA$, and only one of these is in alphabetical order front-to-back. The probability is one in six or $\boxed{\frac{1}{6}}$.
